<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="okr-setting">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>OKRs combine qualitative inspiring goals (Objectives) with quantitative outcome measures (Key Results). KRs must measure outcomes, not tasks; ban task verbs and require baselines.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>okrs</tag>
      <tag>goal-setting</tag>
      <tag>key-results</tag>
      <tag>quarterly-planning</tag>
      <tag>outcomes</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>OKR Setting</title>

    <summary>OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) combine qualitative inspiring goals (Objectives) with quantitative outcome measures (Key Results). The core rule: KRs must be outcomes, not tasks — any KR that starts with "ship/launch/build/release" is a task in disguise and must be rewritten as a measurable metric movement.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Without a structured goal framework, teams either set unmeasurable goals ("improve the product") or rigid task lists that survive even when the strategy changes. OKRs fix this by separating the ambition (Objective) from the measurement (KR), enabling teams to pivot implementation while preserving the goal. The 70% confidence target prevents sandbagging and creates psychological safety for stretch goals.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quarterly goal-setting with 2-50 person teams that need shared focus</item>
        <item>Mid-sized org with 3-5 strategic priorities that must cascade across teams</item>
        <item>Solo creator or founder using OKRs to focus a self-directed quarter</item>
        <item>Aligning a cross-functional initiative (eng + design + marketing) on shared outcome metrics</item>
        <item>Existing goal system is broken — everyone "achieved 100%" or no one tracks</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-PMF startup where every week pivots — OKRs become stale before the quarter ends; use weekly bets instead</item>
        <item>Agencies or consultancies where every project is a deliverable — billable utilization tracking beats OKRs</item>
        <item>Pure delivery teams (compliance, internal IT) — OKRs need outcome variability that does not exist in service work</item>
        <item>Org with no metric infrastructure — KRs that require new instrumentation will fail because the data never arrives</item>
        <item>Psychologically unsafe culture — OKRs are amplifiers; in fear-driven orgs they devolve into sandbagging or punishment</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="structure">
      <p>Defines what makes a valid Objective and Key Result, the scoring scale, and the structural rules.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Objectives must be qualitative, inspiring, time-bound, and memorable. They must not contain numbers. Any Objective that contains a percentage or count is a Key Result in disguise.</statement>
        <rationale>Objectives set direction; Key Results measure progress toward it. Mixing them destroys the separation that makes OKRs useful — if the Objective already contains the number, the KR adds nothing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Limit to 3-5 Objectives per quarter. More than 5 is a strategic failure — everything is important means nothing is. Solo creators should limit to 1 Objective with 3 KRs.</statement>
        <rationale>Focus is the primary value OKRs provide. An OKR set with 8 Objectives tells the team to work on everything, which is indistinguishable from having no OKRs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Key Results must be outcomes, not outputs. Ban the verbs ship/launch/build/release/create/design/implement/deploy at the start of any KR. KRs starting with these verbs are tasks, not outcomes.</statement>
        <rationale>KRs measure whether the Objective was achieved, not whether work was done. "Ship feature X" can be 100% complete while the Objective fails entirely.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Every KR requires a baseline number stated on the day the OKRs are committed. No baseline equals no commitment. If the metric is not yet instrumented, write "TO BE INSTRUMENTED by [owner] by [date]" — never invent a baseline number.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a baseline, "improve from X to Y" is undefined. Teams with no baseline cannot track progress and will report subjective completion at quarter end.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Target confidence at 70% (stretch but achievable). KRs with 100% confidence are sandbagged. KRs with 30% confidence are fantasy. Score 0.7 as ideal; 0.0-0.3 = failed, 0.4-0.6 = progress, 0.7-1.0 = success.</statement>
        <rationale>The 70% target creates psychological safety for ambitious KRs. If hitting 100% is expected, teams anchor to safe targets. If 70% is the norm, teams stretch.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Never couple OKRs to compensation. Any KR linked to individual bonuses will be sandbagged within one quarter. OKRs are learning tools, not performance ratings.</statement>
        <rationale>Compensation coupling converts stretch goals into low-risk targets and destroys the candor required for honest quarterly retrospectives.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Valid Objective and Key Results">
        <note>Objective: "Delight early adopters and earn their advocacy." Qualitative, inspiring, does not contain a number, clearly time-bound to the quarter.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Invalid: number in Objective">
        <note>Objective: "Increase NPS to 50." This is a Key Result. The Objective should be "Build a product users love and recommend."</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="process">
      <p>Sequential steps from strategy alignment through weekly tracking cadence.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 1 — Align to strategy. Inputs: company mission/vision, annual goals, previous quarter's learnings and scores, current market conditions. The anchoring question: "What must we accomplish this quarter to move toward our vision?"</statement>
        <rationale>OKRs disconnected from strategy are vanity. The "why this matters" sentence per Objective is more important than the Objective wording itself. Lose the why and OKRs become prose.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 2 — Draft Objectives by brainstorming. Ask: "What is most important right now?", "If we could only achieve one thing, what would it be?", "What would make this quarter a success?" Limit to 3-5 Objectives maximum.</statement>
        <rationale>Brainstorming before constraining prevents anchoring to last quarter's OKRs. The single-thing question forces prioritization before KRs are written.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 3 — Define Key Results for each Objective. For each KR: how will we know we achieved the Objective? What metric matters? What is the specific target? What is today's baseline? Can it be measured without building new instrumentation?</statement>
        <rationale>The instrumentation question prevents phantom KRs — KRs that sound measurable but require 6 weeks of data pipeline work before they can be tracked at all.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 4 — Validate. Check: Objectives are qualitative, KRs are measurable outcomes (not tasks), 70% confidence per KR, connected to higher-level goals, total count is focused.</statement>
        <rationale>Validation before commitment catches KR-as-task and missing baselines when they are cheapest to fix — before the quarter starts.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 5 — Communicate and commit. Share with stakeholders, get explicit buy-in, make visible on a shared dashboard or wiki. Add a kill condition per Objective: "We drop this Objective if [leading indicator] does not move by week 6."</statement>
        <rationale>Kill conditions prevent OKR theatre — beautiful OKRs that no one acts on. A kill condition forces a mid-quarter honest assessment rather than waiting for the retrospective.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Step 6 — Track weekly with confidence (High/Med/Low), not progress percent. Confidence is forward-looking; percent is backward-looking. Score KRs at end of quarter on 0.0-1.0 scale. Append to the record; do not replace it.</statement>
        <rationale>Confidence tracking surfaces risk earlier. A KR at 80% progress with Low confidence is a bigger problem than a KR at 30% progress with High confidence. Weekly appends preserve the trend history that the retrospective depends on.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <p>Common failure modes that produce OKR theatre or sandbagging, with root causes.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>KR-as-task: "Launch feature X by Q2", "Ship the mobile redesign", "Build the reporting dashboard." The KR is a task disguised as an outcome.</description>
        <reason>Tasks can be 100% complete while the Objective fails entirely. "Launch feature X" is done when the deploy button is pressed; "Increase feature adoption from 10% to 30%" is done when users actually use it. Apply the banned-verb list: ship/launch/build/release/create/design/implement/deploy.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing baseline: "Improve NPS" or "Increase conversion rate to 8%" with no starting number. Teams cannot determine whether progress is being made.</description>
        <reason>Without a baseline, 0.7 KR scoring is subjective. Teams will always report "significant improvement" regardless of actual movement. Every KR committed without a baseline becomes a vehicle for post-hoc rationalization.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Sandbagging: KRs set at 100% confidence that the team knows it will achieve. End-of-quarter scores cluster at 0.95-1.0.</description>
        <reason>Results from coupling OKRs to compensation or from cultures that punish misses. Safe KRs produce zero strategic information. The 70% confidence target is designed to produce ~70% scores at quarter end — teams that consistently score above 0.85 are not stretching.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>OKR theatre: OKR documents are created, weekly check-ins are performed as ritual, no real behavior change occurs. Everyone "achieved" their OKRs.</description>
        <reason>OKRs without a kill condition and without genuine leadership accountability are performative. The kill condition per Objective ("drop this if leading indicator does not move by week 6") is the mechanism that converts OKRs from documentation into decision tools.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Cascading dilution: by the time a company-level Objective cascades to an IC, it has been restated at every level and is now either unrecognizable or trivially achievable.</description>
        <reason>Each level of cascade should add resolution, not copy the level above. A team OKR should decompose the company Objective into the specific contribution the team makes, not paraphrase it.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Too many OKRs: 8 Objectives with 4 KRs each. The team works on all of them equally, which is equivalent to having no priorities.</description>
        <reason>The purpose of OKRs is to declare what is NOT being worked on, not to document everything that will be worked on. More than 5 Objectives means everything is important, which means nothing is.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-integration">
      <p>How autonomous agents integrate OKR methodologies into product workflows.</p>

      <p>A drafting agent ingests the company strategy + previous quarter's learnings + current baselines and proposes 3 candidate Objectives, each with 3 candidate KRs (specific, baselined, time-bound). A challenger agent attacks every KR for being a task, missing baseline, or trivial — proposes revisions. A cascade agent generates draft team OKRs that ladder up to company OKRs without simply restating them. A weekly-tracker agent reads metric dashboards, scores progress, and drafts the check-in summary. Human PM owns final wording and prioritization; humans must own the "why this matters" line per Objective.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: A drafter agent (Opus) — strategic decomposition; needs the strongest reasoning model. A KR-challenger agent (Sonnet) — single job: identify task-disguised-as-KR and missing baselines. A cascade agent — generates team-level OKRs from company OKRs and flags duplicates. A weekly-tracker agent — connects to metrics layer, scores 0.0-1.0, drafts narrative. faion-mlp-impl-planner-agent — once OKRs are set, plans the experiments under each KR.</p>

      <p>Prompt pattern for drafting OKRs: "Strategy: &lt;company strategy and current state&gt;. Previous OKRs and their final scores: &lt;list&gt;. Baselines: &lt;current numbers for candidate KRs&gt;. Propose 3 candidate Objectives. For each: Objective: inspiring, qualitative, max 10 words | 3 KRs: each numeric, baselined, time-bound, outcome (not task) | Why this matters: 1-2 sentences linking to strategy. Reject any KR that starts with 'ship/launch/build/release'."</p>

      <p>Prompt pattern for KR validation: "You are the KR-challenger. For each KR below, decide: Is this a task or an outcome? (if task, rewrite or delete) Is the baseline stated? (if not, demand baseline) Is the target ambitious? (&gt;30% movement from baseline preferred) Is the metric instrumentable? (if requires new tracking, flag) Output: diff with rationale per change."</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Core principles for running successful OKR cycles.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>3 Objectives, 3 KRs each, max. More is wishful, not focus.</statement>
        <rationale>Constraint breeds clarity and accountability.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Every KR has a baseline number on the day OKRs are committed. No baseline = no commitment.</statement>
        <rationale>Baseline makes the commitment measurable and falsifiable.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Decouple OKRs from compensation. The moment money is on the line, sandbagging dominates.</statement>
        <rationale>Bonus coupling destroys honesty and stretch thinking.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Score weekly with confidence (high/med/low), not progress-percent — confidence is forward-looking, percent is backward.</statement>
        <rationale>Confidence predicts outcome; percent is historical.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>The "why this matters" sentence is more important than the wording of the Objective. Lose the why and OKRs are vanity prose.</statement>
        <rationale>Strategic alignment is the foundation of useful OKRs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Commit a kill condition per Objective: "we drop this if X by week 6." Keeps you honest.</statement>
        <rationale>Kill conditions prevent sunk-cost bias from extending failing OKRs.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Solo creators: limit to 1 Objective with 3 KRs per quarter. More than that is fantasy.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-person capacity requires extreme focus.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Common failure modes when LLMs design or execute OKRs.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs produce gorgeous Objective prose ("delight users with magical experiences") that has zero strategic content. Force "why this matters" tied to a specific business reality.</description>
        <reason>Language models optimize for inspirational tone, not strategic clarity. Without grounding, they produce pleasant-sounding non-statements.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Models default to KRs-as-tasks because shipping is concrete. Apply a hard banned-verb list: ship/launch/build/release/create/design/implement/deploy.</description>
        <reason>Task-oriented language is more natural to language models than outcome-oriented language.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Baselines get hallucinated. Require explicit baseline citation (dashboard URL, query, or "TO BE INSTRUMENTED" with owner).</description>
        <reason>Models will invent plausible numbers without grounding.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Cascade agents flatten everything — team OKRs become a restatement of company OKRs. Force decomposition: each level adds resolution, not a copy.</description>
        <reason>Restatement is easier and more coherent than genuine decomposition.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Weekly tracker agents over-write the narrative every week, hiding trend. Append, do not replace.</description>
        <reason>Models optimize for each-week coherence, not trend history.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Human-in-loop checkpoint: final OKR set requires explicit human sign-off; agents are too eager to ship the draft.</description>
        <reason>Models prioritize output generation over quality gates.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Human-in-loop checkpoint: end-of-quarter scoring is sensitive — agents will over-credit progress to look successful. Require human review of final 0.0-1.0 scoring.</description>
        <reason>Models have bias toward positive narratives.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Coupling OKRs to AI-driven performance reviews is a category error. Do not let agents auto-translate KR scores into individual performance ratings.</description>
        <reason>This conflates learning metrics with evaluation metrics, destroying both.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/okr-template.md" purpose="Quarterly OKR document with baseline/target/current/score table per KR"/>
      <template path="templates/kr-lint.py" purpose="Python linter: fails OKR YAML files containing task-shaped or unbaselined KRs"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://felipecastro.com/en/okr/what-is-okr/"/>
      <link href="https://www.lennysnewsletter.com/p/are-okrs-still-a-thing"/>
      <link href="https://rework.withgoogle.com/guides/set-goals-with-okrs/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
